				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I only use + and - labels for labels within a routine. I find myself using a lot of ++ and +++ labels as well, but it's not hard to manage. I also have my code organized fairly well (or at least I try), so finding a label isn't hard. Everything falls into "Code" or "Data". Within "Code", I have all code separated by game mode, so that's either like "TitleScreen", "Cutscene", "Game", etc. It's the same with Data, too. Then within those categories, everything is categorized into even smaller subcategories until you reach an individual object or routine. So this label:
<br />
<br />Data.Cutscene.IntroScene.Frame1.SpriteMap
<br />
<br />Points to the sprite map of "frame 1" in the "intro scene", which is categorized under the "cutscene" group of the data section. Using this notation really helps organizing everything so you don't have some label like "loadsprites" or something ambiguous.
<br />
<br />Looking at this, I see I will definitely stay away from NESASM, as there is no way in hell it would tolerate that label.</div>

					
